SHL Conversational Assessment Recommender
Approach Document

1. Project Overview
This project presents a conversational recommendation system that assists recruiters and hiring
managers in selecting suitable SHL Individual Test Solutions. Rather than relying on simple
keyword matching, the system interprets natural language requests, identifies hiring intent, and
recommends appropriate assessments from the SHL catalogue. The application has been
implemented as a stateless FastAPI service in accordance with the assignment specification. Every
request contains the complete conversation history, allowing the agent to understand context
without maintaining server-side session data. The design emphasizes reliability, modularity,
scalability, and ease of maintenance while ensuring that every recommendation is grounded in the
SHL catalogue.

2. System Architecture
The application is organized into independent modules for API handling, conversational reasoning,
retrieval, and catalogue storage. FastAPI exposes the required endpoints, while the agent module
manages dialogue flow including clarification, recommendation, refinement, comparison, and
refusal. The retrieval component performs semantic search using SentenceTransformers and
FAISS. Separating responsibilities into dedicated modules improves readability, simplifies
debugging, and allows future enhancements without affecting the overall architecture.

3. Retrieval Strategy
The complete SHL catalogue is converted into dense vector embeddings using the
all-MiniLM-L6-v2 SentenceTransformer model. These embeddings are indexed using FAISS,
enabling efficient nearest-neighbour search even for large catalogues. During execution, the user
query is embedded and compared against indexed catalogue entries. The highest-ranking
assessments are retrieved and converted into structured recommendation objects containing the
assessment name and official SHL catalogue URL. This semantic retrieval approach performs
better than exact keyword matching because it captures contextual similarity between user requests
and catalogue descriptions.

4. Conversation Design
The conversational workflow follows four major behaviours defined in the assignment. First,
vague requests trigger clarification questions requesting information such as job role, skills, or
experience. Second, once sufficient context is available, the system retrieves between one and ten
relevant assessments. Third, if the user changes requirements during the conversation, the latest
request is processed together with previous conversation history so recommendations are updated
instead of restarting the interaction. Finally, comparison requests generate grounded explanations
using retrieved catalogue information while off-topic requests are politely refused to maintain
domain boundaries.

5. Design Decisions
A hybrid approach combining deterministic conversation rules with semantic retrieval was selected
because it balances consistency and flexibility. Rule-based logic guarantees predictable behaviour
for clarification, comparison, and refusal scenarios, while vector search provides robust retrieval
for varied natural language expressions. The stateless API design aligns with distributed
deployment environments and simplifies horizontal scaling. FastAPI was selected for its
performance, automatic documentation, and straightforward request validation.

6. Testing and Evaluation
Testing was performed using representative scenarios including vague hiring requests,
role-specific recommendations, refinement across multiple conversation turns, comparison queries,
and off-topic prompts. Responses were verified for schema compliance, recommendation count,
URL correctness, and conversation completion status. Particular attention was given to ensuring
that recommendations originated exclusively from the SHL catalogue and that clarification
occurred before recommendations whenever insufficient information was available.

7. Future Enhancements
Future improvements include learning-based intent classification, reranking retrieved assessments
using cross-encoders, richer catalogue metadata, and explanation generation based entirely on
retrieved evidence. Additional automated evaluation datasets and logging could further improve
robustness and retrieval quality while maintaining strict grounding in the official SHL catalogue.

8. Conclusion
The completed solution demonstrates a modular conversational recommendation system that
combines semantic search, structured dialogue management, and FastAPI deployment. The
architecture satisfies the required API specification while remaining maintainable and extensible.
The retrieval-based design reduces hallucinations by grounding responses in catalogue data and
provides a practical foundation for future production enhancements.